JB, 

Thanks for your quick reply.  Unfortunately, I get the same error when I change new  
FooTest() to FooTest.suite().  I&#39;m using JUnit 3.8.1 if that matters.  

After a peek at the JUnit source, I think we need a completely different Test  
implementation for this so we can write  

    public static final class BarTest extends ObjectTestSuite { ... }  

Here&#39;s a first draft below.  Though far from complete, it works for my trivial  
example.  What do you think?  

Thanks again,  
Nate  



public abstract class ObjectTestSuite extends Assert implements Test {  
    protected ObjectTestSuite() {  
        testMethods = new ArrayList();  
        for (Class theClass = getClass(); theClass != ObjectTestSuite.class; theClass  
= theClass.getSuperclass()) {  
            final Method[] methods = theClass.getDeclaredMethods();  
            for (int i = 0; i &lt; methods.length; ++i) {  
                if (isPublicTestMethod(methods[i])) {  
                    testMethods.add(methods[i]);  
                }  
            }  
        }  
    }  

    public final int countTestCases() {  
        return testMethods.size();  
    }  

    public final void run(final TestResult testResult) {  
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; testMethods.size(); ++i) {  
            try {  
                testResult.startTest(this);  
                ((Method) testMethods.get(i)).invoke(this, new Class[0]);  
                testResult.endTest(this);  
            }  
            catch (final Exception e) {  
                e.printStackTrace();  
            }  
        }  
    }  

    private static boolean isPublicTestMethod(final Method method) {  
        return isTestMethod(method) && Modifier.isPublic(method.getModifiers());  
    }  

    private static boolean isTestMethod(final Method method) {  
        return method.getParameterTypes().length == 0 &&  
                method.getName().startsWith(&quot;test&quot;) &&  
                method.getReturnType().equals(Void.TYPE);  
    }  

    private final ArrayList testMethods;  
}  


